---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SectionContainer from '../components/SectionContainer.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import { clinic, site } from '../lib/site';

// FAQ master page (Manus audit task 7C / GEO). Consolidates the most common
// questions across the whole practice. FAQPage schema + visible accordions —
// one of the most GEO-friendly formats for AI citation. All answers ryan-voice
// + Ohio-compliant (calibrated language, scope boundaries, working alongside PCP).
const sections = [
  {
    heading: 'Chiropractic Care',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'What chiropractic techniques does Dr. DeNome use?',
        a: "Dr. DeNome is trained in Diversified, Thompson, Gonstead, and the Webster Technique for prenatal patients. His preference is manual, specific adjustments: focused, hands-on work matched to the person on the table. Lower-force and gentler approaches are available when a patient prefers them or the clinical picture calls for it.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Is chiropractic care safe?',
        a: "Chiropractic adjustment is a well-established, conservative form of care. We tailor the approach to the person on the table: gentler methods for kids, prenatal patients, acute flare-ups, and sensitive nervous systems. And we coordinate with your physician whenever the situation calls for it.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Does it hurt to get adjusted?',
        a: "Most patients describe adjustments as relieving rather than painful. Mild soreness afterward is possible, similar to how you feel after a good workout, especially in the first few visits. We always explain what we're doing before we do it.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How many visits will I need?',
        a: "It depends on what's going on and how long it's been there. Acute issues may ease in a handful of visits; longer-standing patterns usually take more time as the body adapts. We map out an expected plan after your first visit rather than committing you to an open-ended package up front.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Health Restoration & Lab Testing',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'What is functional health testing?',
        a: "Functional testing runs deeper panels than a standard sick-visit workup, looking at how your systems are functioning rather than only screening for disease. Test, don't guess: the results may reveal patterns a standard workup wasn't designed to look for. It all works alongside your conventional care, never in place of it.",
      },
      {
        q: 'What labs do you run?',
        a: "The most common: the DUTCH panel for hormones, a complete thyroid panel with antibodies, comprehensive stool analysis for gut function, a cardiometabolic panel, and food sensitivity testing. We choose based on your story, not a one-size list. Tests are recommended, never required.",
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the DUTCH test?',
        a: "DUTCH stands for Dried Urine Test for Comprehensive Hormones. It maps your sex hormones, adrenal hormones, and (the part most tests skip) the metabolites that show how your body uses and clears those hormones. You'll find more detail on our dedicated DUTCH test page.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Do I need a doctor’s referral for lab testing?',
        a: "No. You can self-refer for chiropractic care or a health restoration visit. If you have recent labs from another provider, bring them. We'd rather build on what exists than duplicate testing unnecessarily.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How long until I get my results?',
        a: "Most functional panels take about two to three weeks to come back. Then we sit down with the actual report, walk through what each section means in plain language, and build your care plan around the findings.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Pricing & Insurance',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'Do you take insurance?',
        a: "We're a cash-pay practice. That keeps us free to spend the time, run the testing, and recommend the care your situation calls for rather than what an insurance code allows. We can provide a superbill on request for out-of-network reimbursement, but we don't bill insurance directly.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How much does a visit cost?',
        a: "Pricing is flat and posted publicly on our pricing page. Every new patient visit is $99, whichever arm you start with. For chiropractic, that covers your history, exam, X-rays if they're clinically needed, and your first adjustment. For health restoration, it covers your intake conversation and a review of any prior labs. Follow-up adjustments are $50 with soft tissue work, cupping, and scraping included. No surprise bills, no hidden fees.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How much does lab testing cost?',
        a: "It depends on which panels we run. For a patient with no recent testing, first-day lab spend usually lands between $300 and $700. Labs are billed separately and transparently: we confirm the cost of every panel before you order it, and nothing lands on your bill that you didn't agree to first.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Do you accept HSA and FSA cards?',
        a: "Yes. HSA and FSA cards are accepted for both visits and most lab panels.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Your First Visit',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'What happens at my first visit?',
        a: "We sit down and you tell us the story (the actual story, not the seven-minute version) while we listen for the pattern. Chiropractic patients get a thorough exam, with X-rays only if they're clinically needed, and most receive their first adjustment the same day. Health restoration patients walk through their history and any prior labs. Either way, you leave with a clear next step and no pressure to commit before you've slept on it. You have options.",
      },
      {
        q: 'What should I bring?',
        a: "Any recent labs and imaging, your current medications and supplements, and a brief history of when symptoms started and what you've already tried. Pediatric or pregnant patients should bring relevant records. Comfortable clothing is fine. You don't need to change for an exam.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How long is the first appointment?',
        a: "Plan on 60 to 75 minutes for a new patient visit and exam. Follow-up adjustments and review-of-findings visits typically run 20 to 30 minutes.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Pediatric & Prenatal',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'Do you treat children?',
        a: "Yes. We provide pediatric chiropractic care from newborns onward, using soft, age-appropriate adjustments. Families often come for support with sleep, feeding, behavioral regulation, and immune resilience, alongside their pediatrician's care.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Is chiropractic safe during pregnancy?',
        a: "Yes, with a provider trained for it. Dr. DeNome is certified in the Webster Technique, developed specifically for pregnant patients. We position you comfortably and use gentle, pregnancy-appropriate adjustments, coordinating with your OB or midwife.",
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the Webster Technique?',
        a: "A chiropractic adjustment designed for pregnancy that focuses on pelvic alignment, without twisting, cracking, or popping. By easing tension across the pelvis, it may support optimal fetal positioning and a more comfortable pregnancy. It's a useful part of a complete birth team.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Are newborn adjustments safe?',
        a: "Newborn adjustments are extremely gentle, about the pressure you'd use to test the ripeness of a tomato. Birth can leave subtle tension patterns in a baby's spine, especially after a long or instrument-assisted delivery, and gentle care may support the nervous system as the baby develops.",
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    heading: 'Working With Us',
    items: [
      {
        q: 'Do I have to stop seeing my regular doctor?',
        a: "No, and we'd rather you didn't. We work alongside your primary care physician and any specialists you're seeing. Functional testing may fill in parts of the picture a standard workup doesn't cover; your physician still manages medications, referrals, and acute care.",
      },
      {
        q: 'Where are you located and what areas do you serve?',
        a: `We're at ${clinic.address.streetAddress}, ${clinic.address.addressLocality}, ${clinic.address.addressRegion} ${clinic.address.postalCode}. We serve patients across Mason, West Chester, Loveland, Lebanon, and the greater Cincinnati area. Free parking on-site, accessible ground-level entrance.`,
      },
      {
        q: 'Are virtual consultations available?',
        a: "Yes. Virtual health restoration consultations (lab review, nutrition guidance, follow-up care) are available for patients outside the immediate Mason and Cincinnati area. In-person chiropractic care requires being in the clinic.",
      },
      {
        q: 'How do I schedule?',
        a: `The fastest way is to book online through our self-registration link, or call the clinic at ${clinic.phone} during office hours. A real person answers. No phone tree.`,
      },
    ],
  },
];

const allFaqs = sections.flatMap((s) => s.items);

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: allFaqs.map((f) => ({
    '@type': 'Question',
    name: f.q,
    acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a },
  })),
};

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: site.url },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'FAQ', item: `${site.url}/faq` },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FAQ | Chiropractor in Mason, OH"
  description="Answers to common questions about chiropractic care, functional lab testing, pricing, your first visit, and pediatric & prenatal care at The Wellness Way - Mason."
  jsonLd={[faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema]}
>
  <SectionContainer width="default" spacing="md" background="paper-soft">
    <Breadcrumbs trail={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'FAQ' }]} />
    <h1>
      <span class="page-kicker">Frequently Asked Questions</span>
      Straight answers, before you ever book.
    </h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Chiropractic care, lab testing, pricing, first visits, pediatric and prenatal care:
      here's what patients ask us most, answered the way we'd answer in the room.
      Don't see your question? <a href="/contact">Reach out</a> and we'll answer it.
    </p>
  </SectionContainer>

  <SectionContainer width="prose" spacing="md">
    {sections.map((section) => (
      <div class="faq-section" data-reveal="up-sm">
        <h2>{section.heading}</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          {section.items.map((f) => (
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>{f.q}</summary>
              <p>{f.a}</p>
            </details>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </SectionContainer>

  <SectionContainer width="prose" spacing="lg" background="paper-soft">
    <div class="faq-cta" data-reveal>
      <h2>Still have a question? Ask it in person.</h2>
      <p>
        The fastest way to a real answer is a conversation. Book your first visit,
        a flat $99, or call and a real person will pick up during office hours.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <Button href={clinic.bookingUrl} variant="primary" size="lg" external iconAfter>Book Your Appointment</Button>
        <Button href={`tel:${clinic.phoneTel}`} variant="ghost" size="lg">Call {clinic.phone}</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </SectionContainer>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-4xl);
    line-height: 1.1;
  }
  /* SEO keyword string stays inside the H1 as a kicker line; the display
     line underneath carries the visual headline. */
  .page-kicker {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-mute);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .lede {
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 64ch;
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
  }
  .faq-section { margin-bottom: 3.5rem; }
  .faq-section:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .faq-section h2 {
    color: var(--color-ink-strong);
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .faq-list { display: grid; gap: 0.5rem; }
  .faq-item {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    background: var(--color-paper);
    transition: border-color var(--duration-fast) var(--ease-soft);
  }
  .faq-item[open] { border-color: var(--color-brand-primary); }
  .faq-item summary {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-ink-strong);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .faq-item summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .faq-item summary::after {
    content: '+';
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    color: var(--color-brand-primary-dark);
    line-height: 1;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    transition: transform var(--duration-fast) var(--ease-soft);
  }
  .faq-item[open] summary::after { transform: rotate(45deg); }
  .faq-item p {
    margin: 0.75rem 0 0;
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    max-width: 62ch;
  }
  .faq-cta { text-align: center; }
  .faq-cta h2 {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-strong);
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
  }
  .faq-cta p { max-width: 50ch; margin: 0 auto 2rem; color: var(--color-ink-muted); line-height: 1.6; }
  .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    h1 { font-size: var(--text-5xl); }
    .faq-section h2 { font-size: var(--text-4xl); }
    .faq-cta h2 { font-size: var(--text-4xl); }
  }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .faq-cta h2 {
      font-size: var(--text-5xl);
      letter-spacing: -0.022em;
    }
  }
</style>
